servings: 2
---

Boil a full #kettle{}.

Meanwhile, halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125}.

Put the @couscous{120%g} in a large #bowl{}.

Pour in the @boiled water{240%ml}.

Stir in half the @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, then cover tightly with #cling film{}.

Leave to the side for ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat.

Once hot, add the pepper and tomatoes. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Cook, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Meanwhile, drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}.

Once the veg has softened, lower the heat.

Stir in the @tomato puree{30%g} and garlic. Cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute} more.

Add the @chermoula spice mix{1%pack}, chickpeas, @cashew butter{30%g}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water{200%ml} for the sauce and the remaining @vegetable stock paste{10%g}.

Stir together well until the cashew butter is well combined with the sauce.

Bring the stew to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

While it simmers, crumble the @Greek style salad cheese{50%g}.

Once the stew is ready, remove from the heat and season with salt and pepper. Add a splash more water if it's a little thick.

Fluff up the couscous with a #fork{} and share between your bowls.

Spoon over your chickpea, tomato and cashew stew.

Sprinkle over the cheese and @toasted flaked almonds{15%g} to finish.

Enjoy!